04983nam a22007455i 9780801467851DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013947521  a97808014678517 a10.7591/97808014678512doi  a(DE-B1597)478539  a(OCoLC)979723685  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ759.96b.L96 2016 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a306.8753094309021223  aNW 81502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/132307:1 aLyon, Jonathan R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrincely Brothers and Sisters :bThe Sibling Bond in German Politics, 1100–1250 /cJonathan R. Lyon. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b11 charts, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Abbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Origins of Twelfth-Century Princely Lineages -- t2. Forging the Bonds between Siblings: Succession, Inheritance, and Church Careers -- t3. Baby Boomers: The First Generation of the Staufen Upper Aristocracy -- t4. Frederick Barbarossa and Henry the Lion: Cousins in an Age of Brothers -- t5. Cooperation, Conflict, and the Rise of a New Generation, ca. 1180–1210 -- t6. From Bamberg to Budapest: Four Brothers and Four Sisters in the Early Thirteenth Century -- t7. The Uncertain Future of Lineages: Siblings during the Reign of Frederick II -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Genealogical Charts -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Princely Brothers and Sisters, Jonathan R. Lyon takes a fresh look at sibling networks and the role they played in shaping the practice of politics in the Middle Ages. Focusing on nine of the most prominent aristocratic families in the German kingdom during the Staufen period (1138–1250), Lyon finds that noblemen—and to a lesser extent, noblewomen—relied on the cooperation and support of their siblings as they sought to maintain or expand their power and influence within a competitive political environment. Consequently, sibling relationships proved crucial at key moments in shaping the political and territorial interests of many lords of the kingdom.Family historians have largely overlooked brothers and sisters in the political life of medieval societies. As Lyon points out, however, siblings are the contemporaries whose lives normally overlap the longest. More so than parents and children, husbands and wives, or lords and vassals, brothers and sisters have the potential to develop relationships that span entire lifetimes. The longevity of some sibling bonds therefore created opportunities for noble brothers and sisters to collaborate in especially potent ways. As Lyon shows, cohesive networks of brothers and sisters proved remarkably effective at counterbalancing the authority of the Staufen kings and emperors. Well written and impeccably researched, Princely Brothers and Sisters is an important book not only for medieval German historians but also for the field of family history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBrothers and sistersxHistoryxTo 1500xGermany. 0aBrothers and sisterszGermanyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aNobilityxHistoryxTo 1500xGermany. 0aNobilityzGermanyxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801467851423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801467851.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backl